# Chat Command: /test

When the user writes **/test** in chat (either alone or as the only substantive command), execute the following workflow **in order**. Do not skip steps.

## 1. Compile all projects and fix errors

- Run: `dotnet build AutoDocJson.slnx` from repo root `c:\opt\src\AutoDocJson`.
- If the build fails, fix compilation errors (syntax, missing references, etc.) and rebuild until the build succeeds.
- Do not proceed to step 2 until the solution builds with zero errors.

## 2. Run the test program (local C# implementation)

- Run the test project with the TestGeneration mode that uses `TestFileList.json`:
  ```bash
  dotnet run --project AutoDocJson.Tests -- /testGeneration
  ```
- Run from repo root: `c:\opt\src\AutoDocJson`.
- Wait for the process to complete. Note exit code (0 = success, non-zero = failures).

## 3. Evaluate log files for errors after completion (using AI)

- Open and analyze these log files for errors, exceptions, and failures:
  - **Test run log:** `AutoDocJson.Tests\bin\Debug\net10.0\Test-AutoDocGeneration.log` (or same path under the test project output folder).
  - **AutoDocJson app log:** `C:\opt\data\AutoDocJson\` (today’s log file, if present).
  - **Global log (if relevant):** `C:\opt\data\AllPwshLog\<ComputerName>_<yyyyMMdd>.log` for the current date.
- Use AI to summarize: any ERROR/FATAL/FAIL lines, stack traces, failed file names, and whether the run is considered pass or fail.

## 4. Run Chrome remoting to 2 of each type

- Start (or ensure) a web server serving the AutoDocJson output folder, e.g. `C:\opt\Webs\AutoDocJson`, on a known port (e.g. 8765). Use `Serve-AutoDocJson.ps1` or equivalent if needed.
- Using browser remoting (cursor-ide-browser / Chrome), open the search page and then **2 generated doc pages per type**:
  - **CBL:** 2 `.CBL.html` files
  - **BAT:** 2 `.BAT.html` files
  - **PS1:** 2 `.ps1.html` or `.psm1.html` files
  - **REX:** 2 `.REX.html` files
  - **SQL:** 2 `.sql.html` files
  - **C#:** 2 `.csharp.html` files
  - **GS (if present):** 2 `.screen.html` or `.gs.html` files
- Verify each page loads and key elements (tabs, diagrams, content) are present. Note any broken or empty pages.

## 5. Create a short status report (overwrite if exists)

- Write a single status report file that overwrites any previous one.
- **Path:** `c:\opt\src\AutoDocJson\Test-StatusReport.md`
- **Contents (short):**
  - **Date/Time** of the run
  - **Build:** Success / Failed (and brief reason if failed)
  - **Test run:** Exit code, Success count, Failed count (from Test-AutoDocGeneration.results.json or log)
  - **Log evaluation:** Pass / Fail and one or two sentences on errors found (or “No errors”)
  - **Browser check:** Pass / Fail and one sentence on what was checked (2 per type, any issues)
  - **Overall:** PASS or FAIL and optional one-line summary
- Keep the report concise (under one page). Overwrite the file entirely on each /test run.

## Summary

| Step | Action |
|------|--------|
| 1 | `dotnet build AutoDocJson.slnx`; fix errors until build succeeds |
| 2 | `dotnet run --project AutoDocJson.Tests -- /testGeneration` |
| 3 | Read and evaluate Test-AutoDocGeneration.log, AutoDocJson logs, global log; summarize errors with AI |
| 4 | Serve output folder; use Chrome remoting to open 2 docs per type and verify |
| 5 | Write/overwrite `Test-StatusReport.md` with short status (build, test, logs, browser, overall) |

When the user message is **/test**, execute all five steps in order and deliver the status report.
